{{Expand Czech|Karel Klostermann|date=December 2009}} {{Expand German|Karel Klostermann|date=December 2009}} {{Unreferenced|date=July 2008}} ---- [[Image:Klostermann Javornik.JPG|thumb|Statue of Karel Klostermann]] '''Kar(e)l Faustin Klostermann''' (February 13, 1848, in [[Haag am Hausruck]], [[Upper Austria]], [[Austrian Empire]] – July 17, 1923, in [[Štěkeň]], [[Czechoslovakia]]) was a [[Czech language|Czech]] and [[Austria]]n writer. He wrote under the alias ''Faustin''.
From 1857 to 1865 he went to school in [[Písek]], a town in the [[South Bohemian Region]] of what is now the [[Czech Republic]]. He studied medicine until 1869 in [[Vienna]], and was later active as a teacher of [[German language|German]] and [[French language|French]] at the German high school in [[Plzeň]]. He first wrote his works in German; later he turned to the Czech language and wrote novellas about the inhabitants of the middle [[Bohemian Forest]] ({{lang-cs|Šumava}}, {{lang-de|Böhmerwald}}). This can be found in the collection ''V srdci šumavských hvozdů'' ("In the heart of the Šumava"). Some of his novellas are set in and around the town of [[Kašperské Hory]].
Some of his more popular works include ''The son of the free judge'' and ''Fist in stories''.
