With the exception of Thuringian, the East Central German dialects are new dialects resulting from the ''{{lang|de|[[Ostsiedlung]]}}''.{{sfn|Schmidt|2013|p=278}}{{sfn|Paul|1989|p=10}}

== Writing system==

Middle High German texts are written in the [[Latin alphabet]]. There was no standardised spelling, but modern editions generally standardise according to a set of conventions established by [[Karl Lachmann]] in the 19th century.{{sfn|Paul|1989|pp=26ff}} There are several important features in this standardised orthography which are not characteristics of the original [[manuscript]]s:
*the marking of vowel length is almost entirely absent from MHG manuscripts.{{sfn|Paul|1989|p=30}}
*the marking of [[Germanic umlaut|umlauted]] vowels is often absent or inconsistent in the manuscripts.{{sfn|Paul|1989|p=31}}
*a curly-tailed z ({{angle bracket|[[ȥ]]}} or {{angle bracket|ʒ}}) is used in modern handbooks and grammars to indicate the {{IPA|/s/}} or {{IPA|/s/}}-like sound which arose from [[Germanic languages|Germanic]] {{IPA|/t/}} in the [[High German consonant shift]]. This character has no counterpart in the original manuscripts, which typically use {{angle bracket|s}} or {{angle bracket|z}} to indicate this sound.{{sfn|Paul|1989|p=32}}
*the original texts often use {{angle bracket|i}} and {{angle bracket|u}} for the semi-vowels {{IPA|/j/}} and {{IPA|/w/}}.{{sfn|Paul|1989|p=31}}

A particular problem is that many manuscripts are of much later date than the works they contain; as a result, they bear the signs of later scribes having modified the spellings, with greater or lesser consistency, in accord with conventions of their time.{{sfn|Paul|1989|p=29}} In addition, there is considerable regional variation in the spellings that appear in the original texts, which modern editions largely conceal.{{sfn|Paul|1989|p=19}}

===Vowels===

The standardised orthography of MHG editions uses the following vowel spellings:{{sfn|Paul|1989|p=30}}
* [[Short vowels]]: {{angle bracket|a e i o u}} and the umlauted vowels {{angle bracket|ä ö ü}}
* [[Long vowels]]: {{angle bracket|â ê î ô û}} and the umlauted vowels {{angle bracket|æ œ iu}}
* Closing [[diphthong]]s: {{angle bracket|ei ou}}; and the umlauted diphthong {{angle bracket|öu eu oi}}
* Opening [[diphthong]]s: {{angle bracket|ie uo}}; and the umlauted diphthong {{angle bracket|üe}}

Grammars (as opposed to textual editions) often distinguish between {{angle bracket|ë}} and {{angle bracket|e}}, the former indicating the mid-open {{IPA|/ɛ/}} which derived from Germanic {{IPA|/e/}}, the latter (often with a dot beneath it) indicating the mid-close {{IPA|/e/}} which results from primary umlaut of short {{IPA|/a/}}. No such orthographic distinction is made in MHG manuscripts.{{sfn|Paul|1989|p=31}}

===Consonants===
The standardised orthography of MHG editions uses the following consonant spellings:{{sfn|Paul|1989|p=32}}
* [[Stop consonant|Stops]]: {{angle bracket|p t k/c/q b d g}}
* [[Affricate consonant|Affricates]]: {{angle bracket|pf/ph tz/z}}
* [[Fricative consonant|Fricatives]]: {{angle bracket|v f s ȥ sch ch h}}
* [[Nasal consonant|Nasals]]: {{angle bracket|m n}}
* [[Liquid consonant|Liquids]]: {{angle bracket|l r}}
* [[Semivowel]]s: {{angle bracket|w j}}

==Phonology==
The charts show the vowel and consonant systems of classical MHG. The spellings indicated are the standard spellings used in modern editions – there is much more variation in the manuscripts.

